WEBVTT

00:06.089 --> 00:08.967
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:08.967 --> 00:16.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:16.016 --> 00:18.435
<i>- I'm John Stokes;</i>
<i>I'm 25 years old.</i>

00:18.435 --> 00:20.395
I consider myself
a jack of all trades.

00:20.395 --> 00:22.856
I know a little about a lot,
but not a lot about a little.

00:22.856 --> 00:25.901
My yard's slap-full of boats,
four-wheelers, trucks.

00:25.901 --> 00:27.736
I had to get rid
of a lot of stuff,

00:27.736 --> 00:29.488
because my wife is fed up
with all the projects

00:29.488 --> 00:30.989
that I've had.

00:30.989 --> 00:32.491
<i>- My name is Duane Bennet.</i>

00:32.491 --> 00:34.785
My father got me
into blacksmithing.

00:34.785 --> 00:39.039
<i>He's been given a time limit--</i>
<i>he has a heart issue--</i>

00:39.039 --> 00:41.542
<i>and he just wanted</i>
<i>to make a knife.</i>

00:41.542 --> 00:44.044
So I said, "Well,
let's make a knife."

00:44.044 --> 00:46.755
<i>- My name is Drew Hash.</i>
<i>Having been a chef,</i>

00:46.755 --> 00:48.632
I was always working
with knives.

00:48.632 --> 00:50.759
<i>And I kind of got tired</i>
<i>of not getting what I wanted</i>

00:50.759 --> 00:52.594
as far as sharpness
and edge retention.

00:52.594 --> 00:55.597
<i>So I decided</i>
<i>to pursue making knives.</i>

00:55.597 --> 00:57.766
- My name is Quentin Horton.
I've been bladesmithing

00:57.766 --> 01:00.060
for almost 20 years.
I'm prepared

01:00.060 --> 01:02.062
<i>for this competition because</i>
<i>there's not a whole lot</i>

01:02.062 --> 01:03.480
<i>they could throw at me</i>
<i>that I haven't done</i>

01:03.480 --> 01:05.190
<i>at least once.</i>

01:05.190 --> 01:07.234
I could forge
literally with my eyes closed.

01:07.234 --> 01:11.029
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the forge.

01:11.029 --> 01:13.240
You're here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:13.240 --> 01:15.200
of edged-weapon-making
competition,

01:15.200 --> 01:17.077
specifically designed
to push the limits

01:17.077 --> 01:18.829
of weaponsmithing,
all in front

01:18.829 --> 01:21.039
of a panel of expert judges
who decides which of you

01:21.039 --> 01:22.708
will be our next
"Forged in Fire" champion.

01:22.708 --> 01:25.002
leaving here with that check
for 10 grand.

01:25.002 --> 01:26.628
Let's meet them now.

01:26.628 --> 01:29.506
Up first, ABS Master Smith
J. Neilson.

01:29.506 --> 01:31.425
Historic weapons
re-creation specialist

01:31.425 --> 01:33.343
David Baker.
And last,

01:33.343 --> 01:36.722
edged weapons specialist
Doug Marcaida.

01:36.722 --> 01:38.682
Bladesmiths, in this first
round of competition,

01:38.682 --> 01:41.643
you will have to make
not one blade,

01:41.643 --> 01:43.645
but three.

01:43.645 --> 01:46.148
<i>- Thought I was prepared.</i>

01:46.148 --> 01:48.025
I was wrong.
[chuckles]

01:48.025 --> 01:50.319
<i>Never in a million years</i>
<i>did I guess</i>

01:50.319 --> 01:52.612
<i>I was gonna come here</i>
<i>and have to make three blades.</i>

01:52.612 --> 01:54.948
As a bladesmith,
that's the hardest thing

01:54.948 --> 01:56.950
I've ever had
put in front of me.

01:56.950 --> 01:58.535
- Gentlemen, on your anvils
is a cloth.

01:58.535 --> 01:59.494
Go ahead and lift that up.

01:59.494 --> 02:01.330
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:01.330 --> 02:03.165
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

02:03.165 --> 02:05.834
- [laughs]
- Those are everyday,

02:05.834 --> 02:07.919
run-of-the-mill
railroad spikes.

02:07.919 --> 02:11.340
<i>- Oh, boy.</i>
<i>I've only made two of those.</i>

02:11.340 --> 02:13.675
Not my favorite.
They are harder to forge

02:13.675 --> 02:15.469
<i>than regular knife steel.</i>

02:15.469 --> 02:17.304
I'm not looking forward
to this.

02:17.304 --> 02:19.598
- Railroad spike knives
can be simple and rustic,

02:19.598 --> 02:21.725
<i>or they can be elegant</i>
<i>and fantastic.</i>

02:21.725 --> 02:23.727
<i>But they must keep</i>
<i>some semblance</i>

02:23.727 --> 02:26.480
<i>of the spike itself</i>
<i>by maintaining and refining</i>

02:26.480 --> 02:28.106
<i>the spike head.</i>

02:28.106 --> 02:30.275
Your finished blades
at the end of round two

02:30.275 --> 02:32.861
will be tested for strength
and durability

02:32.861 --> 02:35.864
in a railroad spike chop,
and for edge retention

02:35.864 --> 02:38.200
in a canvas runner slice.

02:38.200 --> 02:41.161
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

02:41.161 --> 02:44.164
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your time starts...

02:44.164 --> 02:46.541
Now.

02:46.541 --> 02:49.419
<i>[rousing music]</i>

02:49.419 --> 02:51.922
- First time we've had
our smiths forge three knives

02:51.922 --> 02:53.799
in a challenge,
so I'm really curious to see

02:53.799 --> 02:55.133
what's gonna happen.
Is the first one

02:55.133 --> 02:57.260
gonna be the best,
or the last one?

02:57.260 --> 03:00.263
- Railroad spikes was
all I used to work on,

03:00.263 --> 03:01.932
<i>so I'm comfortable with them.</i>

03:01.932 --> 03:03.433
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:03.433 --> 03:05.102
<i>But the "wow factor" for me</i>

03:05.102 --> 03:06.812
<i>is having to make three knives</i>

03:06.812 --> 03:08.480
<i>in three hours.</i>
<i>I have no idea</i>

03:08.480 --> 03:09.648
<i>how I'm gonna get through it.</i>

03:09.648 --> 03:11.316
- Let's talk a little strategy.

03:11.316 --> 03:14.569
Do you work one blade
at a time, or do you try

03:14.569 --> 03:16.780
to mold the cast?
- I'd put two spikes in

03:16.780 --> 03:19.032
so I can work one, heat one.

03:19.032 --> 03:21.618
Three might be
a little too much to control.

03:21.618 --> 03:24.121
- As of right now, I'm gon' try
to get two knives going

03:24.121 --> 03:25.956
at the same time,
and then I'm gonna take

03:25.956 --> 03:27.791
more time on the third one.

03:27.791 --> 03:30.001
<i>I'm hoping I can keep</i>
<i>my mind set on the fact</i>

03:30.001 --> 03:32.754
that I have three knives.
Hopefully I don't mess one up

03:32.754 --> 03:34.005
thinking about another one.

03:34.005 --> 03:35.257
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:35.257 --> 03:37.134
<i>- My plan of attack</i>

03:37.134 --> 03:38.468
<i>is to work all three blades</i>
<i>at the same time,</i>

03:38.468 --> 03:39.553
<i>because it's more efficient.</i>

03:39.553 --> 03:40.804
The risk in doing it that way

03:40.804 --> 03:42.764
<i>would be I get too caught up</i>

03:42.764 --> 03:45.684
in one aspect of the blade.
My wife would tell you, uh,

03:45.684 --> 03:48.353
more times than not, I go out
to the shop to work and,

03:48.353 --> 03:49.855
<i>"No, that's all right, babe.</i>
<i>I'll be in in, like,</i>

03:49.855 --> 03:51.314
<i>half an hour."</i>
<i>Next thing I know,</i>

03:51.314 --> 03:53.024
I've got sucked into
what I'm doing,

03:53.024 --> 03:57.612
and it's four and a half
hours later, and she's mad.

03:57.612 --> 04:00.824
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

04:00.824 --> 04:02.826
<i>- There are any number</i>
<i>of things that can go wrong</i>

04:02.826 --> 04:05.036
<i>just making one</i>
<i>railroad spike knife.</i>

04:05.036 --> 04:07.914
<i>Now, add two more knives</i>
<i>and a time challenge,</i>

04:07.914 --> 04:10.083
<i>it ups the stakes.</i>
<i>It's gonna be tough</i>

04:10.083 --> 04:11.877
working the logistics.

04:11.877 --> 04:14.754
<i>Do I try and run all three</i>
<i>at the same time?</i>

04:14.754 --> 04:17.382
<i>Do I do one at a time?</i>
<i>I'm gonna make</i>

04:17.382 --> 04:20.260
three different knives
because it showcases

04:20.260 --> 04:22.679
what my abilities are.

04:22.679 --> 04:25.599
<i>It's a challenge for me</i>
<i>to do three different things</i>

04:25.599 --> 04:27.726
that will serve
the same purpose

04:27.726 --> 04:30.854
but have
totally different looks.

04:30.854 --> 04:33.231
- I like the idea
of seeing some differences

04:33.231 --> 04:34.983
in all three blades.
- Yeah, well,

04:34.983 --> 04:37.068
and different styles
all the way around.

04:37.068 --> 04:38.904
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:38.904 --> 04:40.947
<i>- I'm trying to get ahead</i>
<i>of the game</i>

04:40.947 --> 04:43.742
as fast as possible,
so I'm going full-bore.

04:43.742 --> 04:45.410
All three in the fire
at the same time.

04:45.410 --> 04:47.162
<i>I figure</i>
<i>I can slow down later,</i>

04:47.162 --> 04:49.289
<i>but I certainly don't</i>
<i>want to be behind.</i>

04:49.289 --> 04:51.166
- You know,
Drew used to be a chef.

04:51.166 --> 04:52.751
Do you think that
that helps him

04:52.751 --> 04:55.128
in this competition?
- As stress management,

04:55.128 --> 04:57.589
it might help him a lot.
- And honestly, forging knives

04:57.589 --> 04:59.841
is following a recipe, so.

04:59.841 --> 05:02.260
<i>- Having the best ingredients</i>
<i>mixed with years of experience</i>

05:02.260 --> 05:03.804
and knowledge
is what's gonna get you

05:03.804 --> 05:05.222
a superior product.

05:05.222 --> 05:07.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:07.474 --> 05:10.560
- Are we expecting to see tangs
or handles at the end

05:10.560 --> 05:12.103
of this round?
- I'm expecting to see

05:12.103 --> 05:13.939
integral handles.

05:13.939 --> 05:15.524
<i>- My plan is to make</i>
<i>an integrated handle</i>

05:15.524 --> 05:17.150
<i>on all three of my knives.</i>

05:17.150 --> 05:19.152
I figured if I can do
a simple twist handle,

05:19.152 --> 05:21.571
<i>I can have more time</i>
<i>on the actual profile</i>

05:21.571 --> 05:23.156
<i>of the blade.</i>
- Look at this.

05:23.156 --> 05:25.283
John's putting some twists
in his blade,

05:25.283 --> 05:29.079
which is a common trait
for a railroad spike knife.

05:29.079 --> 05:32.749
- One of the standard mistakes
is before you twist the handle,

05:32.749 --> 05:35.168
draw it out a little bit.
Get another 1/2 inch,

05:35.168 --> 05:37.963
three-quarter length.
You see way too many guys

05:37.963 --> 05:39.297
who are just starting out
with spikes

05:39.297 --> 05:41.258
making these thin
little needles.

05:41.258 --> 05:42.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:42.968 --> 05:45.178
<i>- Typically, the spike</i>
<i>has been twisted</i>

05:45.178 --> 05:47.931
into a handle shape.

05:47.931 --> 05:51.101
<i>The problem with that is it'll</i>
<i>tear your hand to pieces,</i>

05:51.101 --> 05:53.186
<i>so I'm taking</i>
<i>a different route.</i>

05:53.186 --> 05:55.814
- I'm curious, here.
Quentin is just flattening

05:55.814 --> 05:58.233
that spike out,
head and everything.

05:58.233 --> 06:00.569
So I think he's actually
planning on putting scales

06:00.569 --> 06:02.404
or something on it.

06:02.404 --> 06:03.905
<i>- I want to take this material</i>
<i>and convert it</i>

06:03.905 --> 06:05.407
into a usable stock,
and make something

06:05.407 --> 06:07.242
that I can actually
put handles on.

06:07.242 --> 06:09.202
- Oh, God.

06:09.202 --> 06:12.706
Quentin has cut
the pommel head off.

06:12.706 --> 06:14.207
- We didn't tell them
to make signature blades

06:14.207 --> 06:15.792
in their signature style.
We told them,

06:15.792 --> 06:17.544
"Make railroad spike knives."

06:17.544 --> 06:20.380
- A railroad spike knife
resembles a railroad spike.

06:20.380 --> 06:22.632
- If you can't look at it
and say, "Hey,

06:22.632 --> 06:25.719
that was a spike..."
- It defeats the purpose.

06:25.719 --> 06:28.179
- 90 minutes has elapsed!
That is half the time

06:28.179 --> 06:29.973
in this first round
of competition!

06:29.973 --> 06:31.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:31.892 --> 06:33.894
- There's
the railroad spike shape

06:33.894 --> 06:36.688
that Duane's working on.
<i>- For the blade shapes,</i>

06:36.688 --> 06:39.691
I'm gonna be basically
doing them on the fly.

06:39.691 --> 06:42.235
<i>When I draw it out,</i>
<i>see what it looks like,</i>

06:42.235 --> 06:44.154
that's just what it's gonna be.

06:44.154 --> 06:46.323
- I'm not quite sure
where that one's going.

06:46.323 --> 06:49.284
- Duane kind of has a long,
I don't know,

06:49.284 --> 06:51.536
parallel edge thing
with a big hook

06:51.536 --> 06:53.288
at the back of it.
I'd like to see him

06:53.288 --> 06:55.373
get more shape into that blade.

06:55.373 --> 06:58.752
- Most people look at me
and I don't smile

06:58.752 --> 07:02.380
a whole lot, so they're like,
"He just looks kinda grumpy

07:02.380 --> 07:05.091
"all the time."
But I'm happy,

07:05.091 --> 07:07.969
I'm easygoing.
I'm smiling on the inside.

07:07.969 --> 07:09.971
That's just me.

07:09.971 --> 07:12.766
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:12.766 --> 07:16.811
- I am loving Drew's design
because he's left the semblance

07:16.811 --> 07:21.024
of what a railroad spike was.

07:21.024 --> 07:23.276
- I wanted
to keep it recognizable

07:23.276 --> 07:26.279
as a railroad spike
without having a big nasty butt

07:26.279 --> 07:29.074
<i>on the end of the knife.</i>
<i>So I'm gonna make--</i>

07:29.074 --> 07:32.661
it's almost like an eagle claw
or something.

07:32.661 --> 07:35.080
<i>It wraps around the outside</i>
<i>of your hand.</i>

07:35.080 --> 07:38.166
It's--may not
be super functional.

07:38.166 --> 07:40.085
Feels good in the hand, though.

07:40.085 --> 07:42.796
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:42.796 --> 07:45.840
<i>- My next step is to start</i>
<i>refining that profile.</i>

07:45.840 --> 07:48.259
- Oh, hey, look at that.
- Look at that.

07:48.259 --> 07:50.845
- Quentin has just turned
one of our grinders

07:50.845 --> 07:53.264
90 degrees onto its side.

07:53.264 --> 07:55.767
These grinders have always
had this capability.

07:55.767 --> 07:58.895
It's the first time
we've seen anybody utilize it.

07:58.895 --> 08:01.231
<i>- The benefit of using</i>
<i>that grinder</i>

08:01.231 --> 08:04.359
<i>in a horizontal position,</i>
<i>the convex edge of that wheel</i>

08:04.359 --> 08:06.695
is less surface area,
so it's removing material

08:06.695 --> 08:08.863
much, much faster that way.

08:08.863 --> 08:11.032
- There are only
45 minutes remaining

08:11.032 --> 08:14.244
in this first round
of competition!

08:14.244 --> 08:16.496
<i>- All three of my knives,</i>
<i>they're forged out.</i>

08:16.496 --> 08:20.667
But I know that I didn't put
a whole lot of profile

08:20.667 --> 08:22.961
onto these blades
like most other smiths would.

08:22.961 --> 08:25.964
Mine look
like thinned-out spikes.

08:25.964 --> 08:28.383
- While John has put twists
in his handles,

08:28.383 --> 08:30.802
his blade continues
to stay thin.

08:30.802 --> 08:33.054
<i>- I'm just gonna</i>
<i>keep my knives pretty narrow</i>

08:33.054 --> 08:35.807
and hope for the best,
but I gotta get rid of

08:35.807 --> 08:37.892
<i>any imperfections</i>
<i>that I can find.</i>

08:37.892 --> 08:40.603
Hammer dents.
Hopefully no cracks.

08:40.603 --> 08:42.564
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:42.564 --> 08:44.691
<i>- I got all my blades ready</i>
<i>to heat treat.</i>

08:44.691 --> 08:47.027
I'll put one in,
and I'll get it to thermocycle,

08:47.027 --> 08:49.571
so while it's cooling down
I'm heating up another one.

08:49.571 --> 08:52.032
Once one's ready, then I can
set it off to the side

08:52.032 --> 08:54.117
and I can work on the next one.

08:54.117 --> 08:56.870
- When we go to strength tests,
we have a lot of broken blades

08:56.870 --> 08:59.164
because guys don't thermocycle.

08:59.164 --> 09:02.000
So this is nice to see.
<i>- Railroad spikes</i>

09:02.000 --> 09:04.294
<i>are softer steel,</i>
<i>because they're not made</i>

09:04.294 --> 09:06.713
to get hard, they're made
to take the stresses

09:06.713 --> 09:08.590
<i>of the railroad.</i>

09:08.590 --> 09:11.593
<i>So they're not</i>
<i>particularly good knife steel.</i>

09:11.593 --> 09:14.429
Great letter-opener steel.

09:14.429 --> 09:15.680
- One of the blades
has been quenched.

09:15.680 --> 09:19.809
Whoo-hoo!
- Only 11 more to go.

09:19.809 --> 09:21.603
- Call that one good.

09:21.603 --> 09:24.272
- Oh, there we go.
- That's two for Duane.

09:24.272 --> 09:27.525
- It feels great to have
this much time on the clock

09:27.525 --> 09:30.528
and have almost all my blades
heat-treated.

09:30.528 --> 09:32.405
- You're all quenched?
- I got two of 'em done.

09:32.405 --> 09:33.907
- All straight?
- Yeah.

09:33.907 --> 09:35.241
- Nice.
- Hard, too.

09:35.241 --> 09:37.410
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:37.410 --> 09:40.497
- Working next to Duane
was a lot like the days

09:40.497 --> 09:42.123
when I was working
in a restaurant next to a cook

09:42.123 --> 09:43.833
<i>who I meshed with really well.</i>

09:43.833 --> 09:45.960
Just having another person
next to you

09:45.960 --> 09:48.338
who you are comfortable with
is a big deal.

09:48.338 --> 09:50.215
- I need to do some grinding
before I quench.

09:50.215 --> 09:52.425
- Got it.
<i>- I'm gonna clean up</i>

09:52.425 --> 09:54.302
<i>the profile of the blades.</i>

09:54.302 --> 09:57.639
I got a little bit of warpage,
some thick areas.

09:57.639 --> 09:59.933
I'm gonna clean all of that up.

09:59.933 --> 10:03.436
- I really am surprised
at how thick Drew's blades look

10:03.436 --> 10:05.063
from here.
- That's good.

10:05.063 --> 10:06.689
He can grind them down,
get all the scale off

10:06.689 --> 10:09.901
if he wants to make 'em
really nice looking.

10:09.901 --> 10:12.195
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:12.195 --> 10:13.613
- Did Quentin
just quench a blade?

10:13.613 --> 10:15.740
- Yep, quenched the first one.

10:15.740 --> 10:17.826
- Quenched first blade,
no problems.

10:17.826 --> 10:20.495
Nice and straight.

10:20.495 --> 10:22.580
- Now there's two.

10:22.580 --> 10:25.041
- That's two blades quenched
for Quentin.

10:25.041 --> 10:27.710
- [bleep].
<i>The second blade...</i>

10:27.710 --> 10:29.462
Not so much.

10:29.462 --> 10:31.089
It's dead soft.

10:31.089 --> 10:33.550
Oh, crap.
- Did he go back into the fire?

10:33.550 --> 10:34.717
Did he put--
- I think he went back

10:34.717 --> 10:36.636
into the forge,
he's not done yet.

10:36.636 --> 10:39.013
- Quentin's got multiple blades
in the fire at once.

10:39.013 --> 10:41.015
- Oh, that worries me
with heat treat.

10:41.015 --> 10:42.851
You don't want to be
quenching one blade

10:42.851 --> 10:44.936
worrying about
if the other is overheating.

10:44.936 --> 10:47.147
<i>- If I have to waste time</i>
<i>re-hardening this blade,</i>

10:47.147 --> 10:51.234
how long until I move on
to the next blade?

10:51.234 --> 10:53.278
<i>If I don't get it hard,</i>

10:53.278 --> 10:55.405
<i>then I'm pretty much</i>
<i>going home.</i>

10:55.405 --> 10:59.409
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:59.409 --> 11:01.286
<i>- The second blade...</i>

11:01.286 --> 11:03.121
It's nowhere close to hard.

11:03.121 --> 11:05.039
- Did he go back into the fire?
Did he put--

11:05.039 --> 11:08.168
- I think he went back into
the forge, he's not done yet.

11:08.168 --> 11:09.919
<i>- If I don't get it hard,</i>

11:09.919 --> 11:12.505
<i>then I'm pretty much</i>
<i>going home.</i>

11:12.505 --> 11:14.048
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

11:14.048 --> 11:16.009
- Now there's two.

11:16.009 --> 11:19.637
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:19.637 --> 11:21.723
<i>- The blade did get</i>
<i>significantly harder,</i>

11:21.723 --> 11:24.684
<i>but there wasn't a whole lot</i>
<i>of time for the third quench.</i>

11:24.684 --> 11:27.562
And, well, my brain just starts
to panic a little bit.

11:27.562 --> 11:31.399
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:31.399 --> 11:34.485
- So it looks like John's
got one of his blades quenched.

11:34.485 --> 11:36.571
<i>- First quench,</i>
<i>everything's hardened.</i>

11:36.571 --> 11:38.489
- Second blade going in.

11:38.489 --> 11:41.242
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:41.242 --> 11:43.203
- I definitely don't want
anything to go wrong.

11:43.203 --> 11:45.747
This is the heart and soul
of the blade.

11:45.747 --> 11:47.999
Hard as glass.

11:47.999 --> 11:50.668
<i>Second quench works out great,</i>
<i>I'm hard all the way through.</i>

11:50.668 --> 11:52.462
One more to go.
Third time's the charm.

11:52.462 --> 11:55.089
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:55.089 --> 11:58.635
- I'm very surprised
at how quickly Duane

11:58.635 --> 12:01.387
has turned out three blades.
<i>- I didn't think</i>

12:01.387 --> 12:04.849
that I would be this far along
at this time, so I'm--

12:04.849 --> 12:06.684
I'm really excited
that I have enough time

12:06.684 --> 12:09.687
to clean up and grind
and get what I want.

12:09.687 --> 12:11.940
<i>I like a clean blade.</i>

12:11.940 --> 12:14.817
I'm not real fond
of the rustic look.

12:14.817 --> 12:16.861
There we go.

12:16.861 --> 12:18.613
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

12:18.613 --> 12:21.282
- So Drew's got
one blade quenched.

12:21.282 --> 12:22.951
<i>- I'm doing one at a time.</i>

12:22.951 --> 12:26.037
The first one,
I'm confident with everything.

12:26.037 --> 12:27.830
- Drew's gotta be feeling
the pressure now,

12:27.830 --> 12:30.750
because he knows he's got
two more blades

12:30.750 --> 12:33.419
that need to be quenched,
and he hasn't left a lot

12:33.419 --> 12:36.923
of room in his timeline
to correct any deficiencies

12:36.923 --> 12:38.800
or errors that might occur.

12:38.800 --> 12:41.719
- The second one
didn't have any issues.

12:41.719 --> 12:44.472
One more blade,
but I'm running out of time.

12:44.472 --> 12:46.975
<i>I have to get</i>
<i>this one perfect.</i>

12:46.975 --> 12:48.768
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:48.768 --> 12:54.315
- Five, four, three,
two, one.

12:54.315 --> 12:56.025
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines!

12:56.025 --> 12:59.195
Drop your tools!
This round is over!

12:59.195 --> 13:02.031
Four contestants, 12 knives.

13:02.031 --> 13:05.159
The more that we raise the bar,
the more these guys rise

13:05.159 --> 13:06.911
to the occasion.
<i>- This was</i>

13:06.911 --> 13:09.580
a very difficult challenge.
Never in my life

13:09.580 --> 13:11.416
have I thought
that I was gonna have to work

13:11.416 --> 13:14.419
on three different blades
in a three-hour span.

13:14.419 --> 13:16.421
Now I just hope
that the judges like them

13:16.421 --> 13:18.047
<i>as much as I do.</i>

13:18.047 --> 13:19.173
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:19.173 --> 13:22.176
- Three hours, 12 knives.

13:22.176 --> 13:25.096
We asked,
you guys delivered.

13:25.096 --> 13:27.181
Now it's time for the judges
to take a closer look

13:27.181 --> 13:29.600
at your work.
John, you're up first.

13:29.600 --> 13:31.769
Please present your blades
to the judges.

13:31.769 --> 13:33.604
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:33.604 --> 13:36.607
- It's got that classic,
traditional twist handles.

13:36.607 --> 13:38.609
A little of this hammer work
is uneven.

13:38.609 --> 13:40.403
You can see on this blade
how it's thinner here

13:40.403 --> 13:43.740
and fatter here.
I'd love to see these blades

13:43.740 --> 13:45.950
get lined up
with their handles.

13:45.950 --> 13:47.410
- Right now,
this is for butter,

13:47.410 --> 13:49.537
this is for jam.

13:49.537 --> 13:52.457
What I want with this set
is to give it more character,

13:52.457 --> 13:57.462
and have one for the vampire,
for the zombie, and the mummy.

13:57.462 --> 13:59.589
- I think Doug Marcaida
just called your set of knives

13:59.589 --> 14:02.300
a tea set.
- [chuckles]

14:02.300 --> 14:04.552
- Duane, you're up.
Please present your blades

14:04.552 --> 14:06.846
to the judges.

14:06.846 --> 14:08.681
- This is what I think of
when I think

14:08.681 --> 14:10.892
of a classic
railroad spike knife.

14:10.892 --> 14:12.935
Keep the head on there
as a pommel and a grip,

14:12.935 --> 14:15.313
twist the handle,
and draw your blade out.

14:15.313 --> 14:17.523
I would have liked a little
more drop in the handle.

14:17.523 --> 14:19.609
This kind of kicks up
in the back a little bit.

14:19.609 --> 14:21.402
But you did a really good job.

14:21.402 --> 14:24.197
- I like the blade profile
on this one.

14:24.197 --> 14:26.282
You still have a semblance
of what it was,

14:26.282 --> 14:28.785
with the spike head being
on that end of the blade.

14:28.785 --> 14:31.370
So you go
from a railroad spike knife--

14:31.370 --> 14:33.915
it's evolving into something
that seems

14:33.915 --> 14:37.502
to have lost its identity.
I'm all about evolution

14:37.502 --> 14:40.129
as long as tradition's
not forgotten.

14:40.129 --> 14:41.839
- All right, Drew, you're up.

14:41.839 --> 14:45.093
Please present your blades
to the judges.

14:45.093 --> 14:46.552
- I like what you've got
going here.

14:46.552 --> 14:48.638
That hook at that back
is great.

14:48.638 --> 14:50.556
That's not going anywhere.

14:50.556 --> 14:52.683
And it keeps
that railroad spike theme

14:52.683 --> 14:54.727
going through these knives.

14:54.727 --> 14:55.812
These are really
beautifully done.

14:55.812 --> 14:57.855
- Thank you.

14:57.855 --> 15:00.566
- Quentin, please present
your blades to the judges.

15:00.566 --> 15:02.318
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:02.318 --> 15:05.154
- They're all nice
traditional hunter shapes.

15:05.154 --> 15:06.989
The biggest problem
I have with these

15:06.989 --> 15:10.576
is I can't tell
that they were railroad spikes.

15:10.576 --> 15:12.578
We lost the theme.

15:12.578 --> 15:15.373
You took the heads off,
so they look like blades

15:15.373 --> 15:17.667
that were forged
out of a railroad spike.

15:17.667 --> 15:21.129
They don't look like
railroad spike knives anymore.

15:21.129 --> 15:23.381
- Bladesmiths,
the judges and I

15:23.381 --> 15:26.384
need to go into deliberation.
While we do that,

15:26.384 --> 15:28.052
I'm gonna ask you
to please leave your blades

15:28.052 --> 15:30.096
here on the table
and step off the forge floor.

15:30.096 --> 15:33.141
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

15:33.141 --> 15:35.476
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:35.476 --> 15:37.353
- I'd really like to be a fly
on the wall in there.

15:37.353 --> 15:38.938
- [chuckles]

15:38.938 --> 15:41.149
- I'm seeing two smiths
on this table

15:41.149 --> 15:43.192
that absolutely stuck
to the theme.

15:43.192 --> 15:46.779
John and Drew.
Do you guys agree?

15:46.779 --> 15:49.782
However, two smiths here
went off the rails.

15:49.782 --> 15:51.284
<i>I'm gonna start with Duane.</i>

15:51.284 --> 15:53.077
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:53.077 --> 15:55.204
- Duane's got a whole
transition going here.

15:55.204 --> 15:58.332
This is the classic
railroad spike.

15:58.332 --> 16:00.793
This one--I mean, he's still
got the head on there.

16:00.793 --> 16:02.837
I really like the blade.

16:02.837 --> 16:05.047
This piece
I just don't really care for.

16:05.047 --> 16:08.092
I feel like my hand's
gonna slip up on this edge.

16:08.092 --> 16:10.970
And this is more like a knife
that was forged

16:10.970 --> 16:15.099
from a railroad spike,
not a railroad spike knife.

16:15.099 --> 16:17.101
- All right, let's move on
to our last bladesmith.

16:17.101 --> 16:19.478
That's Quentin.
- I don't want to look.

16:19.478 --> 16:21.314
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

16:21.314 --> 16:24.317
- They're really functional
hunter-type shapes.

16:24.317 --> 16:26.402
Put all that aside,

16:26.402 --> 16:28.779
I don't see
a railroad spike anywhere.

16:28.779 --> 16:30.573
He cut the spike heads
right off.

16:30.573 --> 16:33.534
- Those spike heads are what's
unique about this knife,

16:33.534 --> 16:36.829
and he doesn't have them
on any of his three blades.

16:36.829 --> 16:41.959
I do not see even a basic
railroad spike knife.

16:41.959 --> 16:45.004
- So, all that stuff taken
into consideration,

16:45.004 --> 16:46.172
Doug, have you made
your final decision?

16:46.172 --> 16:47.340
- Yes, I have.
- Dave?

16:47.340 --> 16:48.507
- Uh, yeah.
- J?

16:48.507 --> 16:49.425
- Oh, yeah.
- All right.

16:49.425 --> 16:51.761
Let's go tell our smiths.

16:51.761 --> 16:53.888
Bladesmiths,
the judges have completed

16:53.888 --> 16:56.933
their deliberation, and they've
made a final decision.

16:56.933 --> 16:58.726
The bladesmith
leaving the forge is...

16:58.726 --> 17:02.855
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:02.855 --> 17:04.398
Quentin.

17:04.398 --> 17:06.776
Your blades
did not make the cut.

17:06.776 --> 17:09.737
- Quentin, you gave us three
very well-made knives

17:09.737 --> 17:11.656
out of railroad spikes.

17:11.656 --> 17:13.324
But when you cut
those spike heads off,

17:13.324 --> 17:15.076
you lost the very part
that makes that

17:15.076 --> 17:16.994
a classic railroad spike knife.

17:16.994 --> 17:18.955
That's why
we're letting you go.

17:18.955 --> 17:20.831
- That's fair.
- Quentin.

17:20.831 --> 17:23.334
Please surrender your blades.

17:23.334 --> 17:25.419
<i>- Right now,</i>
<i>I'm not feeling great.</i>

17:25.419 --> 17:28.256
I'm as happy as I can be
with the products I put out

17:28.256 --> 17:30.383
<i>in the time frame</i>
<i>that I was given.</i>

17:30.383 --> 17:33.678
<i>But, regardless of how well</i>
<i>my knives look,</i>

17:33.678 --> 17:36.430
they're not recognizable
as spike knives.

17:36.430 --> 17:38.808
I gave it everything
I could give it.

17:38.808 --> 17:41.978
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:41.978 --> 17:44.313
- Bladesmiths, congratulations.
You've made it

17:44.313 --> 17:46.524
to the second round
of this competition.

17:46.524 --> 17:48.150
Now it's time
to turn your blades

17:48.150 --> 17:50.611
into fully-functional
railroad spike knives

17:50.611 --> 17:53.364
by finishing off the handles.

17:53.364 --> 17:55.992
Your finished blades
will be tested for strength

17:55.992 --> 17:58.578
and durability
in a railroad spike chop,

17:58.578 --> 18:02.415
and for edge retention
in a canvas runner slice.

18:02.415 --> 18:04.041
Good luck, bladesmiths.

18:04.041 --> 18:05.751
Your three hours starts...

18:05.751 --> 18:06.961
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:06.961 --> 18:09.505
Now.

18:09.505 --> 18:12.592
John has done traditional
railroad spike knives.

18:12.592 --> 18:14.885
The handles are already done.

18:14.885 --> 18:16.387
- Duane.
Three different blades,

18:16.387 --> 18:18.139
three different profiles
that require

18:18.139 --> 18:20.850
completely different
techniques.

18:20.850 --> 18:22.560
- Duane's just gotta figure out
what he's gonna do,

18:22.560 --> 18:24.604
that third knife especially.

18:24.604 --> 18:26.564
- Drew.
- Well, he set himself up

18:26.564 --> 18:28.024
for a lot of work.
Now he's gotta

18:28.024 --> 18:29.734
put handle scales
on three knives

18:29.734 --> 18:32.028
and shape the handles
so they're comfortable.

18:32.028 --> 18:35.197
- We've seen smiths fail
putting two scales on

18:35.197 --> 18:38.492
in three hours.
He's got six scales.

18:38.492 --> 18:40.369
- Right now, I don't really
have a strategy.

18:40.369 --> 18:41.996
I'm just working
on time management,

18:41.996 --> 18:44.123
and gonna try to get
as much done

18:44.123 --> 18:46.792
as fast as possible.
I think if I just had one blade

18:46.792 --> 18:49.378
<i>my hands would be full.</i>
<i>The fact that there's three</i>

18:49.378 --> 18:51.380
is really kicking my butt.

18:51.380 --> 18:53.007
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:53.007 --> 18:55.092
- I gotta work
on the ugly duckling.

18:55.092 --> 18:57.887
<i>It's past the spike stage.</i>
<i>I can't put the head back on,</i>

18:57.887 --> 19:01.641
<i>but I can make it</i>
<i>as pretty as possible.</i>

19:01.641 --> 19:03.768
If I fall into that, you know--
I'm trying to make

19:03.768 --> 19:06.896
<i>this one blade just right.</i>
<i>Next thing I know,</i>

19:06.896 --> 19:10.107
<i>I don't have enough time</i>
<i>to do the rest.</i>

19:10.107 --> 19:12.985
<i>[exciting music]</i>

19:12.985 --> 19:15.655
- What is John gonna do
for the next three hours?

19:15.655 --> 19:19.283
- I would like to see more
characteristics on that blade.

19:19.283 --> 19:21.118
- The judges said
that my blades

19:21.118 --> 19:22.787
were a
butter-and-cream-cheese set.

19:22.787 --> 19:24.872
<i>But at this point,</i>
<i>there's nothing I can do</i>

19:24.872 --> 19:27.124
<i>to draw the belly out,</i>
<i>so I'm focusing</i>

19:27.124 --> 19:29.418
on getting these blades
realigned

19:29.418 --> 19:31.003
and getting them
straightened up.

19:31.003 --> 19:33.422
- Oh, no, that's not
a good way of doing this.

19:33.422 --> 19:35.091
He's not locking anything
in a vice.

19:35.091 --> 19:36.467
- He's using another set
of vice grips...

19:36.467 --> 19:37.927
- Oh, no.
- To try to do some twisting.

19:37.927 --> 19:39.679
- He had a wet rag
around the blade,

19:39.679 --> 19:41.347
and now the wet rag is off.

19:41.347 --> 19:43.265
So hopefully that heat
doesn't start travelling down

19:43.265 --> 19:44.725
into his blade,
'cause he really will

19:44.725 --> 19:47.186
have to heat treat them again.

19:47.186 --> 19:50.189
- Now, I hope Drew
marked his blades

19:50.189 --> 19:53.359
and his handle material,
because it'd be very easy

19:53.359 --> 19:55.486
to mix up the handle scales.

19:55.486 --> 19:58.155
Then it's chaos.
- Oh, man, that scared me.

19:58.155 --> 20:00.908
I never use
five-minute epoxies,

20:00.908 --> 20:03.494
which is my only option
at this point.

20:03.494 --> 20:06.414
Uh, oh.
<i>For my third knife,</i>

20:06.414 --> 20:09.417
I get the epoxy
on the wrong side of the scale.

20:09.417 --> 20:11.335
Damn it. Damn it. Damn it.

20:11.335 --> 20:14.255
This epoxy,
it's already freezing up.

20:14.255 --> 20:16.382
<i>I'm freaking out.</i>

20:16.382 --> 20:19.719
I have to work really fast
to get the epoxy off,

20:19.719 --> 20:21.929
or I might have to start over.

20:21.929 --> 20:26.267
<i>I'm starting to think</i>
<i>that I'm not gonna make it.</i>

20:26.267 --> 20:27.309
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

20:27.309 --> 20:28.853
- Oh, man, that scared me.

20:28.853 --> 20:31.063
<i>The three knives</i>
<i>is messing me up.</i>

20:31.063 --> 20:33.649
I'm losing track
of which one is which.

20:33.649 --> 20:37.361
- Be very easy to mix up
the handle scales.

20:37.361 --> 20:39.071
Then it's chaos.

20:39.071 --> 20:41.741
- For my third knife,
I get the epoxy

20:41.741 --> 20:43.284
<i>on the wrong side</i>
<i>of the scale.</i>

20:43.284 --> 20:45.369
Damn it, damn it, damn it.

20:45.369 --> 20:48.289
I have to work really fast
to get the epoxy off,

20:48.289 --> 20:50.332
or I might have to start over.

20:50.332 --> 20:53.002
<i>I have to scrape it off,</i>
<i>flip the pieces</i>

20:53.002 --> 20:55.212
so that
they're properly aligned,

20:55.212 --> 20:56.922
<i>and just move on.</i>

20:56.922 --> 20:58.674
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:58.674 --> 21:00.426
<i>- The judges said,</i>
<i>"This is a classic</i>

21:00.426 --> 21:02.511
<i>"railroad spike knife.</i>

21:02.511 --> 21:04.263
But I would," you know,
"like to see a little bit

21:04.263 --> 21:06.849
more drop in the handle."

21:06.849 --> 21:09.560
- I'd get the, uh, scales
on my other two knives epoxied

21:09.560 --> 21:11.103
and in place
and then start working on that

21:11.103 --> 21:12.605
while it's curing.

21:12.605 --> 21:14.523
Again, it's that
time management thing.

21:14.523 --> 21:16.859
<i>- Any time you're adding heat</i>
<i>to a knife,</i>

21:16.859 --> 21:19.403
you have to be very particular
so that you don't get any

21:19.403 --> 21:20.696
<i>of the heat</i>
<i>travelling up the spine</i>

21:20.696 --> 21:22.907
and, uh,
ruining your heat treat.

21:22.907 --> 21:25.451
<i>If I ruin the heat treat,</i>
<i>the edges are gonna roll,</i>

21:25.451 --> 21:28.329
it could crack.
That is the most important part

21:28.329 --> 21:31.290
of a functional blade.

21:31.290 --> 21:33.250
- You have
just 90 minutes remaining

21:33.250 --> 21:35.127
to finish your work.

21:35.127 --> 21:36.796
<i>- I can't stand finished work.</i>

21:36.796 --> 21:39.632
I would much rather be forging
all day long

21:39.632 --> 21:41.467
<i>and have someone else</i>
<i>sand them out and bevel them</i>

21:41.467 --> 21:44.053
<i>where they need to be.</i>
- John's been at the grinder

21:44.053 --> 21:46.430
for the last 90 minutes.
I suspect

21:46.430 --> 21:48.390
for the remaining 90 minutes
he'll be over there.

21:48.390 --> 21:50.601
- He'll have some nice little,
uh, toothpicks.

21:50.601 --> 21:52.937
They'll be fabulous.
<i>- I'm gon' put a mirror finish</i>

21:52.937 --> 21:55.147
<i>on my blades.</i>
My grinder at home

21:55.147 --> 21:57.858
is a 30 horsepower.
To do this amount of work,

21:57.858 --> 22:00.236
it would take me
at least two days.

22:00.236 --> 22:03.572
<i>But I have to be</i>
<i>very careful with this.</i>

22:03.572 --> 22:06.200
I don't want to make my blade
too thin.

22:06.200 --> 22:08.118
- Drew has got
his blades ground,

22:08.118 --> 22:09.995
he's setting up
for his handles.

22:09.995 --> 22:11.872
- I'm feeling behind.
I've got a lot

22:11.872 --> 22:13.999
of catching up to do.
It's go time.

22:13.999 --> 22:16.502
<i>I need to shape these handles</i>
<i>really fast.</i>

22:16.502 --> 22:19.547
The handle is not
completely refined.

22:19.547 --> 22:21.382
I'm gonna have to live with it.
I'm stopping what I'm doing

22:21.382 --> 22:24.677
and I'm gonna sharpen.
<i>I don't want my edge too thin</i>

22:24.677 --> 22:27.888
because I know
it's gonna be brutalized,

22:27.888 --> 22:31.308
<i>and if I have a real keen,</i>
<i>scalpel-like edge that I love,</i>

22:31.308 --> 22:34.770
it's gonna chip
or possibly break the blade.

22:34.770 --> 22:37.857
- I've got plenty of time.
I don't have a whole lot to do.

22:37.857 --> 22:40.693
- John is at the back
of the forge over there,

22:40.693 --> 22:43.487
and it looks like he might
be acid-etching his blades,

22:43.487 --> 22:46.657
which is kind of a cool accent.

22:46.657 --> 22:49.869
- Got like 30 minutes left,
and I still have a lot to do.

22:49.869 --> 22:51.537
<i>I'm just gonna</i>
<i>have to grind 'em</i>

22:51.537 --> 22:53.747
<i>with the clamps in place.</i>

22:53.747 --> 22:57.376
- I've done all I can do,
and it looks good.

22:57.376 --> 22:59.712
- Is John sitting down
all done?

22:59.712 --> 23:01.714
- Yep.
- I hate to be the guy

23:01.714 --> 23:03.883
<i>that sits down</i>
<i>and just watches.</i>

23:03.883 --> 23:05.926
- John has called it.
<i>- I cannot think</i>

23:05.926 --> 23:07.720
<i>of anything else to do.</i>

23:07.720 --> 23:09.722
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:09.722 --> 23:12.141
- Duane's in scramble mode
right now.

23:12.141 --> 23:13.976
<i>- Am I gonna have enough time</i>
<i>to get my grinding done</i>

23:13.976 --> 23:15.311
<i>so I can get my shaping done?</i>

23:15.311 --> 23:16.937
<i>Are my pins gonna stay put?</i>

23:16.937 --> 23:18.689
<i>It's gonna go</i>
<i>right to the last second</i>

23:18.689 --> 23:20.900
to see if I even
get it all done.

23:20.900 --> 23:26.238
- Five, four, three, two, one.

23:26.238 --> 23:27.865
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

23:27.865 --> 23:31.035
Drop your tools.
This round is over.

23:31.035 --> 23:32.953
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

23:32.953 --> 23:36.707
<i>- Three blades in six hours,</i>
<i>to a finished point</i>

23:36.707 --> 23:38.626
<i>where they can be tested.</i>

23:38.626 --> 23:40.252
<i>That's a pretty</i>
<i>impressive feat, and I'm--</i>

23:40.252 --> 23:42.630
I'm pretty proud of that fact.

23:42.630 --> 23:46.216
- Welcome to our strength test,
bladesmiths.

23:46.216 --> 23:49.345
Gonna take your blades
and beat them repeatedly

23:49.345 --> 23:51.388
into these railroad spikes.

23:51.388 --> 23:53.807
What your blades do
to the spike,

23:53.807 --> 23:55.768
I don't really care.
I wanna see what the spikes

23:55.768 --> 23:57.394
are gonna do to your blades.

23:57.394 --> 23:59.563
- John, you're up first.
You ready?

23:59.563 --> 24:03.651
- Not exactly, but...
- We're gonna do it anyway.

24:03.651 --> 24:05.569
<i>- I'm nervous as hell.</i>

24:05.569 --> 24:08.322
<i>My knives are thinner</i>
<i>than the others.</i>

24:08.322 --> 24:10.324
So I don't know
if I can hang.

24:10.324 --> 24:17.164
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:23.963 --> 24:24.922
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

24:24.922 --> 24:26.548
- Hold up.

24:26.548 --> 24:27.675
I realized that
all three of them

24:27.675 --> 24:29.385
are testing my blades.

24:29.385 --> 24:31.762
<i>Now I'm shook.</i>

24:31.762 --> 24:33.389
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:33.389 --> 24:35.349
[all grunting]

24:35.349 --> 24:38.394
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

24:38.394 --> 24:45.359
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:47.736 --> 24:49.947
- Holy crap.
- No kidding.

24:49.947 --> 24:52.157
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:52.157 --> 24:54.034
- Mm-kay.

24:54.034 --> 24:56.036
Well, John, not bad.

24:56.036 --> 24:58.580
You got a little edge damage,
a little deformation.

24:58.580 --> 25:01.000
A little too soft on this one.

25:01.000 --> 25:04.211
This edge, not bad.
A little brittle.

25:04.211 --> 25:06.088
This one held up the best.

25:06.088 --> 25:09.008
Overall, you survived
the strength test.

25:09.008 --> 25:10.884
Nicely done.
- Thank you.

25:10.884 --> 25:12.678
- Duane, how you feeling?

25:12.678 --> 25:14.888
- Let's do it.

25:14.888 --> 25:17.808
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

25:17.808 --> 25:24.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:24.064 --> 25:26.984
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

25:26.984 --> 25:33.657
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:33.657 --> 25:36.201
Whew.

25:36.201 --> 25:37.286
- All right, guys.

25:37.286 --> 25:40.122
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

25:40.122 --> 25:43.500
All right, Duane.
We got a bit of a problem here.

25:43.500 --> 25:47.755
The edges on your blades
aren't as hard as we hoped.

25:47.755 --> 25:51.300
We don't have chipping,
the steel's actually compacted

25:51.300 --> 25:53.635
in on itself.

25:53.635 --> 25:56.263
Drew, you're up.

25:56.263 --> 25:58.098
How do you feel?
- Nervous.

25:58.098 --> 26:01.226
- Nervous? That's all right.
Be over in a minute.

26:01.226 --> 26:03.270
<i>- I'm completely distraught</i>
<i>inside.</i>

26:03.270 --> 26:05.314
<i>I'm trying</i>
<i>to calm myself down,</i>

26:05.314 --> 26:06.899
<i>doing some deep breathing,</i>

26:06.899 --> 26:09.985
and I'm just stressed out
like crazy.

26:09.985 --> 26:12.905
<i>[rising dramatic music]</i>

26:12.905 --> 26:15.741
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

26:15.741 --> 26:22.706
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:26.168 --> 26:27.795
- All right, Drew.

26:27.795 --> 26:30.464
Your blades are actually
very comfortable,

26:30.464 --> 26:33.759
except for one point:
these hooks back here.

26:33.759 --> 26:36.095
There's sharp corners on there,
and that actually bit

26:36.095 --> 26:37.429
into Dave's hand, here.

26:38.722 --> 26:41.225
- The edges took some damage.

26:41.225 --> 26:43.143
For the most part,
your blades held up well.

26:43.143 --> 26:45.062
So, good job.
- Thank you.

26:45.062 --> 26:47.856
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

26:47.856 --> 26:49.858
- All right, bladesmiths.
It's time to see

26:49.858 --> 26:52.194
what kind of edge
your blades still have.

26:52.194 --> 26:54.655
A sharp edge should cut easily.

26:54.655 --> 26:58.242
A rolled edge, it might snag,
or worse, do nothing at all.

26:58.242 --> 26:59.785
- John, you're up first.
You ready for this?

26:59.785 --> 27:02.412
- I'm ready as I can be.

27:02.412 --> 27:03.789
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

27:03.789 --> 27:04.832
- Got it?

27:04.832 --> 27:08.836
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:08.836 --> 27:11.797
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

27:11.797 --> 27:17.761
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:19.847 --> 27:22.766
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

27:22.766 --> 27:24.560
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:24.560 --> 27:27.104
- All right, John.
All your blades have areas

27:27.104 --> 27:30.524
that are sharp, and some areas
that aren't as sharp.

27:30.524 --> 27:33.360
On the inside of the canvas,
your blades cut.

27:33.360 --> 27:34.778
But on the thick edges,

27:34.778 --> 27:36.405
they had a hard time
cutting through.

27:36.405 --> 27:39.241
But, all your blades will cut.

27:39.241 --> 27:40.617
- Thank you, sir.

27:40.617 --> 27:42.661
- All right, Duane, your turn.
You ready?

27:42.661 --> 27:45.080
- Let's do it.

27:45.080 --> 27:47.833
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

27:47.833 --> 27:50.586
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:50.586 --> 27:53.463
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

27:53.463 --> 28:00.304
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:03.056 --> 28:05.976
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

28:05.976 --> 28:07.561
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:07.561 --> 28:09.521
- All right, Duane.
Overall,

28:09.521 --> 28:13.567
there's a lot of damage
in all the edges, and it shows.

28:13.567 --> 28:16.153
Your blades pretty much
hang up and rip

28:16.153 --> 28:19.114
into the canvas.
They didn't cut.

28:19.114 --> 28:22.826
Overall, your blades will rip.

28:22.826 --> 28:24.578
- All right, Drew, your turn.
You ready?

28:24.578 --> 28:26.788
- Yes, sir.

28:26.788 --> 28:29.917
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

28:29.917 --> 28:32.294
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:32.294 --> 28:35.297
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

28:35.297 --> 28:41.428
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:41.428 --> 28:44.348
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

28:44.348 --> 28:45.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:45.891 --> 28:47.601
- All right, Drew.
There's some areas here

28:47.601 --> 28:50.062
that are damaged, and it was
exactly those areas

28:50.062 --> 28:52.272
that hung up on the canvas.

28:52.272 --> 28:56.485
But overall,
your blades here will cut.

28:56.485 --> 28:57.694
- Thank you.

28:57.694 --> 28:59.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:59.112 --> 29:00.948
- Bladesmiths.

29:00.948 --> 29:02.866
For one of you,
your journey stops

29:02.866 --> 29:05.327
dead in the tracks right here.

29:05.327 --> 29:07.537
The bladesmith
leaving the forge is...

29:07.537 --> 29:11.041
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

29:11.041 --> 29:12.668
Duane.

29:12.668 --> 29:14.878
Your blade did not
make the cut.

29:14.878 --> 29:16.797
- You know, Duane,
though I liked the diversity

29:16.797 --> 29:19.257
of blades you made for us,
your knives suffered

29:19.257 --> 29:20.968
the most damage
in the strength test,

29:20.968 --> 29:22.427
and that was really
made apparent

29:22.427 --> 29:23.887
in the sharpness test,
so that's why

29:23.887 --> 29:25.764
we're letting you go.

29:25.764 --> 29:29.518
- Duane,
please surrender your blades.

29:29.518 --> 29:31.770
<i>- Pretty disappointed,</i>
<i>but I'm gonna go home</i>

29:31.770 --> 29:33.772
with my head held high.

29:33.772 --> 29:36.441
<i>I'm very happy with</i>
<i>what I've accomplished here.</i>

29:36.441 --> 29:38.402
I'm looking forward
to getting back out in the shop

29:38.402 --> 29:42.280
<i>with Dad</i>
<i>and working on some knives.</i>

29:42.280 --> 29:45.033
- John, Drew,
congratulations.

29:45.033 --> 29:46.576
You've made it
to the final round

29:46.576 --> 29:48.370
of this competition.
Now we're sending you back

29:48.370 --> 29:50.789
to your home forges,
to recreate an iconic weapon

29:50.789 --> 29:52.541
from history...

29:52.541 --> 29:56.211
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

29:56.211 --> 29:58.714
The arming sword.

29:58.714 --> 30:00.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:00.590 --> 30:02.551
<i>The arming sword</i>
<i>was the sword of choice</i>

30:02.551 --> 30:04.636
<i>for medieval European knights</i>
<i>during an era</i>

30:04.636 --> 30:07.097
<i>of advanced armor, with swords</i>
<i>needed to penetrate</i>

30:07.097 --> 30:08.765
<i>both armor and flesh.</i>

30:08.765 --> 30:10.892
<i>The blade's point</i>
<i>has a distinctive taper,</i>

30:10.892 --> 30:13.145
<i>allowing pinpoint thrusts</i>
<i>into vulnerable areas</i>

30:13.145 --> 30:15.689
<i>on an enemy.</i>
<i>A central fuller in the blade</i>

30:15.689 --> 30:18.066
<i>reduced its weight,</i>
<i>making it a well-balanced</i>

30:18.066 --> 30:20.027
<i>and effective</i>
<i>one-handed weapon.</i>

30:20.027 --> 30:22.112
<i>Wielded with a shield</i>
<i>in the opposite hand,</i>

30:22.112 --> 30:24.072
<i>knights were protected</i>
<i>as they delivered</i>

30:24.072 --> 30:27.034
<i>deadly blows powerful enough</i>
<i>to cleave a skull in two.</i>

30:27.034 --> 30:30.287
<i>in 1429, French troops</i>
<i>made a heroic counter attack</i>

30:30.287 --> 30:33.123
<i>at the Siege of Orléans,</i>
<i>led by Joan of Arc</i>

30:33.123 --> 30:36.334
<i>wielding the arming sword.</i>

30:36.334 --> 30:38.253
The blade parameters
are as follows:

30:38.253 --> 30:40.338
Your blade must
be double-edged, and include

30:40.338 --> 30:43.008
a central fuller that runs
at least half the length

30:43.008 --> 30:46.511
of the blade on both sides,
a guard that is upswept,

30:46.511 --> 30:48.680
and a disc pommel.

30:48.680 --> 30:52.768
<i>- I probably make</i>
<i>40 kitchen knives a year.</i>

30:52.768 --> 30:57.981
I'm not a sword maker,
so it's gonna be interesting.

30:57.981 --> 30:59.691
- You will have five days
at your home forge

30:59.691 --> 31:01.818
to accomplish this task.
At the end of those five days,

31:01.818 --> 31:03.445
you will return
and present your blades

31:03.445 --> 31:05.072
to our panel of expert judges.

31:05.072 --> 31:06.865
And only after
they've thoroughly tested,

31:06.865 --> 31:08.533
then will they declare
one of you our new

31:08.533 --> 31:10.452
"Forged in Fire" Champion,
who also leaves here

31:10.452 --> 31:12.287
with that check for 10 grand.

31:12.287 --> 31:14.998
Make it happen, gentlemen.
We'll see you in five days.

31:14.998 --> 31:16.958
- Good luck.
- Good luck to you.

31:16.958 --> 31:20.003
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

31:20.003 --> 31:23.548
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:23.548 --> 31:26.176
<i>- Day one of forging</i>
<i>in my home shop,</i>

31:26.176 --> 31:28.512
and I'm basically
making something

31:28.512 --> 31:30.514
<i>completely outside</i>
<i>of my wheelhouse.</i>

31:30.514 --> 31:32.766
<i>I got a lot of movement</i>
<i>still to do,</i>

31:32.766 --> 31:34.935
<i>but I'm confident.</i>

31:34.935 --> 31:37.312
<i>Hopefully by the end of today</i>
<i>I'll have a general shape,</i>

31:37.312 --> 31:40.524
ideally all the forging done,
so that tomorrow I can begin

31:40.524 --> 31:43.110
my normalizing and heat treat.

31:43.110 --> 31:45.403
Luckily I have this press.
I'd probably cry

31:45.403 --> 31:47.155
if I had to do it by hand.

31:47.155 --> 31:50.200
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:50.200 --> 31:52.577
<i>- Back in my home shop,</i>
<i>I'm a lot less anxious.</i>

31:52.577 --> 31:54.704
But I have a lot less
tools here

31:54.704 --> 31:56.790
<i>than I did</i>
<i>in the first couple rounds.</i>

31:56.790 --> 32:00.585
But I can be a lot more careful
and methodical with my hammer

32:00.585 --> 32:02.170
and my anvil.
I've never made a blade

32:02.170 --> 32:04.673
this big before,
so it's gonna definitely

32:04.673 --> 32:07.384
put a strain on what I can
and can't do.

32:07.384 --> 32:10.220
<i>My blade's gonna have</i>
<i>a very simple design,</i>

32:10.220 --> 32:12.514
but I want to show the judges
that I can make more

32:12.514 --> 32:14.349
than just butter knives.

32:14.349 --> 32:16.143
<i>The hardest part</i>
<i>of making this sword, for me,</i>

32:16.143 --> 32:18.520
<i>is gonna be that fuller.</i>
<i>Making sure that it lines up</i>

32:18.520 --> 32:20.856
<i>and I actually get</i>
<i>the indentation like I want</i>

32:20.856 --> 32:22.899
is gonna be a bit
of a challenge.

32:22.899 --> 32:24.734
I can do a lot more
than what I showed

32:24.734 --> 32:27.320
in the first round.

32:27.320 --> 32:29.364
And second round.
[laughs]

32:29.364 --> 32:31.074
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:31.074 --> 32:33.410
- I've got the general length
and profile

32:33.410 --> 32:35.120
of the blade established.

32:35.120 --> 32:37.372
<i>So today I'm going to work</i>
<i>on the fullers</i>

32:37.372 --> 32:39.541
and heat treat.

32:39.541 --> 32:41.710
<i>I've never done a quench</i>
<i>with fullers in,</i>

32:41.710 --> 32:44.129
<i>so I'm not sure</i>
<i>if it'll keep things straight</i>

32:44.129 --> 32:47.048
or make 'em want to warp more.

32:47.048 --> 32:50.510
Moment of truth.

32:52.804 --> 32:58.685
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:58.685 --> 33:02.105
We're good.
It's perfectly straight.

33:02.105 --> 33:04.441
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:04.441 --> 33:06.193
<i>- Just, uh,</i>
<i>got my blade profile</i>

33:06.193 --> 33:11.031
forged out, and I got
my fullers somewhat defined.

33:11.031 --> 33:15.952
Today I have to get my grinding
and my heat treat done.

33:15.952 --> 33:18.747
Never heat-treated anything
this big, this gon' be--

33:18.747 --> 33:20.624
this gon' be
a bit of a challenge.

33:20.624 --> 33:22.876
<i>I really need my heat treat</i>
<i>to go right.</i>

33:22.876 --> 33:24.961
Unlike other days,
I just don't have time

33:24.961 --> 33:27.339
to fall back onto
"make another blade."

33:27.339 --> 33:30.342
<i>I need it to work exactly</i>
<i>the way it's supposed to.</i>

33:30.342 --> 33:33.386
<i>If I get a warp or crack</i>
<i>in my blade with my quench,</i>

33:33.386 --> 33:36.556
I might not be able to turn in
a finished blade.

33:36.556 --> 33:39.476
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

33:39.476 --> 33:42.729
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:42.729 --> 33:44.439
Oh, [bleep].

33:44.439 --> 33:46.191
I caught a warp.

33:46.191 --> 33:48.610
That really sucks.

33:48.610 --> 33:50.570
Gotta heat-treat again.

33:50.570 --> 33:52.906
<i>Going in for a second quench</i>
<i>is really risky.</i>

33:52.906 --> 33:55.325
<i>I'm putting a lot of stress</i>
<i>on a blade that's already</i>

33:55.325 --> 33:57.077
<i>been through a lot of stress.</i>

33:57.077 --> 33:59.287
Things can go bad pretty quick,
but I really need

33:59.287 --> 34:01.289
a straight blade.

34:01.289 --> 34:03.875
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:03.875 --> 34:06.211
Pulling out the second quench,
it's like I'm watching a repeat

34:06.211 --> 34:08.213
of the first one.
It's got a warp,

34:08.213 --> 34:09.965
<i>and I put a lot of pressure</i>
<i>on this blade,</i>

34:09.965 --> 34:12.217
<i>trying to get it</i>
<i>straight again.</i>

34:15.095 --> 34:16.304
<i>[tense music]</i>
That's two quenches in a row
that I can't get

34:16.304 --> 34:17.847
- That's two quenches in a row
that I can't get

34:17.847 --> 34:20.058
a straight blade.
I don't know what it is.

34:20.058 --> 34:22.519
I'm gon' have to heat-treat
this damn thing again.

34:22.519 --> 34:25.397
[bleep].

34:25.397 --> 34:27.190
<i>I don't want to</i>
<i>stress the blade any more</i>

34:27.190 --> 34:29.025
<i>than I have already.</i>

34:29.025 --> 34:31.236
<i>And I got enough meat</i>
<i>to where I can just</i>

34:31.236 --> 34:32.195
grind it straight.

34:33.989 --> 34:36.283
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

34:36.283 --> 34:39.160
<i>- For my final day,</i>
<i>I need to get everything</i>

34:39.160 --> 34:40.996
slapped together.

34:40.996 --> 34:42.998
<i>I have my guard completed,</i>

34:42.998 --> 34:45.917
<i>I have my</i>
<i>wire-wrapped handle done.</i>

34:45.917 --> 34:48.295
Like chef knives, I like
to make each one different,

34:48.295 --> 34:50.338
<i>much like I'm cooking a meal.</i>

34:50.338 --> 34:53.133
<i>It's like no two are the same.</i>
<i>So I'm gonna try to put</i>

34:53.133 --> 34:55.218
<i>some of my personal touches</i>
<i>on this.</i>

34:55.218 --> 34:58.346
I got my guard fit on,
I got my handle going on next.

34:58.346 --> 35:00.557
<i>I'm gonna epoxy it.</i>
<i>I was going</i>

35:00.557 --> 35:05.061
to peen the pommel head over
to secure the whole sword,

35:05.061 --> 35:07.689
and I go to light my torch,
and something's wrong with it.

35:07.689 --> 35:09.399
I already had a plan "B"
in my head,

35:09.399 --> 35:10.900
and that was to weld it.
I think it's gonna

35:10.900 --> 35:15.238
be just as strong
as peening over the pommel.

35:15.238 --> 35:17.741
<i>It worked out fine,</i>
<i>no big deal.</i>

35:17.741 --> 35:19.701
I think I stand
a good chance of winning.

35:19.701 --> 35:22.037
<i>It's been a really fun time.</i>

35:22.037 --> 35:25.081
Might have caught the sword--
the sword fever.

35:25.081 --> 35:27.250
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:27.250 --> 35:30.503
- I need to get my guard handle
and pommel together.

35:30.503 --> 35:33.423
<i>The toughest problem for me</i>
<i>is gettin' all these pieces</i>

35:33.423 --> 35:36.676
<i>to line up and fit together</i>
<i>like it's supposed to.</i>

35:36.676 --> 35:38.928
<i>I'm gonna peen my pommel</i>
<i>onto the tang,</i>

35:38.928 --> 35:41.097
<i>and just for a little</i>
<i>extra support,</i>

35:41.097 --> 35:43.058
<i>I'm gonna tack-weld</i>
<i>the end of the pommel</i>

35:43.058 --> 35:44.559
<i>into the tang.</i>

35:44.559 --> 35:46.645
It's definitely
not coming apart.

35:46.645 --> 35:48.980
<i>It's not gonna look</i>
<i>like a pristine weapon,</i>

35:48.980 --> 35:52.651
<i>it's gonna look like</i>
<i>a old iron sword.</i>

35:52.651 --> 35:56.071
<i>But I made it, and I'm</i>
<i>really proud of myself.</i>

35:56.071 --> 35:58.073
I'm done.
Fun build,

35:58.073 --> 36:00.325
but I'm glad it's over with.

36:00.325 --> 36:03.453
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

36:03.453 --> 36:04.954
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:04.954 --> 36:09.000
- John, Drew.
Welcome back to the forge.

36:09.000 --> 36:11.169
John, tell the judges
about your weapon.

36:11.169 --> 36:13.672
- It was a bit of a challenge
to make that.

36:13.672 --> 36:15.799
I've never made anything
quite that big.

36:15.799 --> 36:19.511
The sword's made from 5160,
and the handle material

36:19.511 --> 36:22.347
is Guatemalan rosewood
and black walnut.

36:22.347 --> 36:25.100
- All right.
Drew, how'd it go for you?

36:25.100 --> 36:27.769
- It was, uh,
incredibly brutal.

36:27.769 --> 36:30.397
By far the toughest, funnest,
and most beautiful thing

36:30.397 --> 36:32.816
I've ever made.
I used some zebrawood

36:32.816 --> 36:34.818
wrapped in steel wire
for the handle

36:34.818 --> 36:37.028
and a little bit of copper
for the pommel.

36:37.028 --> 36:39.114
- Well, it's nice to hear
you brought the best thing

36:39.114 --> 36:42.283
that you've ever made,
'cause you're gonna need it.

36:42.283 --> 36:44.869
The weapons tests start now.

36:44.869 --> 36:46.913
And up first, the kill test.

36:46.913 --> 36:48.957
Doug.

36:48.957 --> 36:50.792
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:50.792 --> 36:52.961
- Bladesmiths,
the arming sword.

36:52.961 --> 36:55.255
It's a cut-and-thrust weapon.

36:55.255 --> 36:57.340
To test the lethality
of your arming sword,

36:57.340 --> 36:59.426
I will deliver
slashes and thrusts

36:59.426 --> 37:01.052
on these pork carcasses.

37:01.052 --> 37:02.637
John, you're up first.
You ready for this?

37:02.637 --> 37:05.265
- Yes, sir.
- Let's do this.

37:05.265 --> 37:08.435
- That hide is super thick.
To get through that,

37:08.435 --> 37:10.687
<i>you really need</i>
<i>a very fine edge</i>

37:10.687 --> 37:12.522
<i>and not a lot of weight</i>
<i>behind it,</i>

37:12.522 --> 37:14.858
and I didn't build that.

37:14.858 --> 37:18.153
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

37:18.153 --> 37:20.864
<i>[heavy electronic music]</i>

37:20.864 --> 37:27.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:33.626 --> 37:35.587
- [grunts]

37:35.587 --> 37:37.547
- All right, John, let's talk
about your arming sword here.

37:37.547 --> 37:39.424
It's heavy.

37:39.424 --> 37:42.177
It did cut on some parts
of the carcass,

37:42.177 --> 37:44.554
other parts
it just bounced off.

37:44.554 --> 37:48.433
Thrusting-wise, though, it did
what it was designed for.

37:48.433 --> 37:51.019
This will kill.
- Thank you, sir.

37:51.019 --> 37:52.479
- All right, Drew, you're up.
You ready?

37:52.479 --> 37:54.981
- Yes, sir.
- Let's do this.

37:54.981 --> 37:57.317
<i>- When I saw John's blade</i>
<i>hit the carcass</i>

37:57.317 --> 38:00.069
<i>the first few times,</i>
<i>it didn't really cut so great.</i>

38:00.069 --> 38:03.156
So I'm worried about
my sharpness on my blade.

38:03.156 --> 38:06.159
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

38:06.159 --> 38:07.577
<i>[heavy electronic music]</i>

38:07.577 --> 38:09.245
- Oh, nice.

38:09.245 --> 38:12.165
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:12.165 --> 38:14.083
- [exhales sharply]

38:14.083 --> 38:19.672
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:19.672 --> 38:22.008
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

38:22.008 --> 38:26.429
- All right, Drew.
This is a very sharp blade,

38:26.429 --> 38:28.556
a great thrusting blade.

38:28.556 --> 38:31.267
And I like how you put
a counterbalance right here,

38:31.267 --> 38:33.853
because all the weight
is nicely distributed

38:33.853 --> 38:36.481
so where I can thrust
and slash.

38:36.481 --> 38:39.025
Your blade, sir, will kill.

38:39.025 --> 38:40.693
- Thank you.
- Good job.

38:40.693 --> 38:42.529
- Thank you.

38:42.529 --> 38:44.823
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

38:44.823 --> 38:47.450
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to our strength test.

38:47.450 --> 38:50.870
One of my favorites--
the ice block chop.

38:50.870 --> 38:52.622
And we super-sized it.

38:52.622 --> 38:54.374
What I'm gonna do is take
each of your swords,

38:54.374 --> 38:56.084
and I'm gonna beat them
repeatedly and viciously

38:56.084 --> 38:58.127
into this big chunk of ice.
It's gonna test

38:58.127 --> 38:59.546
the overall construction
of your sword

38:59.546 --> 39:01.464
as well as
its edge-holding ability.

39:01.464 --> 39:03.508
Now, what your swords do
to the ice is secondary

39:03.508 --> 39:05.802
compared to what the ice
does to your swords.

39:05.802 --> 39:08.555
And John, you're up first.
How you feeling, buddy?

39:08.555 --> 39:09.973
- [chuckles]
Nervous.

39:09.973 --> 39:11.140
- Well, we're gonna
do it anyway, so.

39:11.140 --> 39:12.350
- Yeah.

39:12.350 --> 39:17.981
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:17.981 --> 39:20.984
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

39:20.984 --> 39:24.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:24.571 --> 39:26.906
- [chuckling]

39:26.906 --> 39:28.825
- [laughing]

39:28.825 --> 39:35.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:37.709 --> 39:40.128
[laughing]

39:40.128 --> 39:42.088
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

39:42.088 --> 39:44.507
- [exhales]

39:44.507 --> 39:48.595
Well, this is very heavy.
Very hard to control.

39:48.595 --> 39:52.515
Also, aside from having gaps
in your shoulders here,

39:52.515 --> 39:54.684
you've got a pretty good bend
in the blade,

39:54.684 --> 39:56.853
and that was there
before I started.

39:56.853 --> 40:03.109
Not a lot of edge left,
but you survived.

40:03.109 --> 40:04.694
- Drew, how you feeling?
- I'm ready.

40:04.694 --> 40:06.404
- Good, so am I.

40:06.404 --> 40:09.282
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

40:09.282 --> 40:13.244
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:13.244 --> 40:16.205
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

40:16.205 --> 40:23.129
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:28.259 --> 40:30.970
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

40:30.970 --> 40:35.600
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:35.600 --> 40:37.143
- Now, Drew,
this is a beautiful sword.

40:37.143 --> 40:40.605
- Thank you.
- Blade is still razor-sharp,

40:40.605 --> 40:43.566
which is very impressive
for an ice block chop.

40:43.566 --> 40:45.735
That being said,
the ice block chop

40:45.735 --> 40:47.904
is meant to be brutal.
It's meant to test

40:47.904 --> 40:50.281
the overall structure,
integrity of your sword

40:50.281 --> 40:52.241
from tip to pommel.

40:52.241 --> 40:54.452
Problem is, I'm holding
your pommel in this hand

40:54.452 --> 40:56.037
instead of this hand.

40:56.037 --> 40:57.997
So that's an issue.
- Yeah.

40:57.997 --> 41:00.249
- Drew...

41:00.249 --> 41:02.877
Your blade has suffered
a catastrophic failure.

41:02.877 --> 41:05.088
Have to ask you
to please leave the forge.

41:05.088 --> 41:06.756
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:06.756 --> 41:09.550
<i>- I'm sad</i>
<i>that my blade failed,</i>

41:09.550 --> 41:12.220
but I feel really good
about the fact that I was able

41:12.220 --> 41:14.597
to make something
completely outside

41:14.597 --> 41:16.849
of my wheelhouse.
But none of that matters

41:16.849 --> 41:18.726
if the pommel comes flying off.

41:18.726 --> 41:20.687
<i>If the functionality</i>
<i>isn't there,</i>

41:20.687 --> 41:22.605
<i>the aesthetics</i>
<i>really do not matter.</i>

41:22.605 --> 41:24.440
I had a ton of fun;
I would do it again

41:24.440 --> 41:26.651
in a second.
I'm super excited to get back

41:26.651 --> 41:29.404
to the West Coast
and just get back to work

41:29.404 --> 41:31.197
chipping away
at my custom orders.

41:31.197 --> 41:33.866
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:33.866 --> 41:35.910
- John, congratulations.

41:35.910 --> 41:37.495
You're the next
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:37.495 --> 41:39.956
Good job.
[all clapping]

41:39.956 --> 41:42.208
- Thanks.
- You'll be receiving a check

41:42.208 --> 41:44.085
for $10,000.
How do you feel?

41:44.085 --> 41:46.671
- I didn't want to win
like that, but...

41:46.671 --> 41:48.464
I feel pretty good.

41:48.464 --> 41:50.299
<i>I made butter knives</i>
<i>in the first round.</i>

41:50.299 --> 41:52.468
I come back with a beast
of an arming sword,

41:52.468 --> 41:54.012
and now I'm
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:54.012 --> 41:55.847
- Good job, brother.

41:55.847 --> 41:57.473
<i>- When I get home,</i>
<i>the first thing I'm doing</i>

41:57.473 --> 41:59.434
<i>is buying a press</i>
<i>and get right back out</i>

41:59.434 --> 42:01.019
to the shop
and forge some more.

42:01.019 --> 42:02.895
<i>This is only driving me</i>
<i>to do it more.</i>

42:02.895 --> 42:05.857
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

42:05.857 --> 42:07.692
<i>♪ ♪</i>
